snippet.textDisplay: So an opportunity popped up with a really good find, so I went and bought it for $500!!! This really shows you what you can do to find your first project car, find a budget suv, etc with minimal risk and a lot of potential reward!!! We used all common hand tools and did this job at home ourselves! Craftsman was bought by Stanley and now they have decent tools for the price! Worth taking a look at for sure! I messed with the 150 piece set for the first time and I liked it. It got the job done and I think you guys looking for your first set would find it to be a good starter set! Here is the link to the tool sets: http://bit.ly/2PNfHLS

snippet.textDisplay:
Seems like everything back home is going up in price, except used cars. Shit! Wish I was back home in the states.
"...one screwdriver length..." No, kid..."one screwdriver-blade's thickness"...Don't get so carried away with your self-love that you lose accuracy of language. In technical matters, it is more important than almost anything else, including (perhaps especially) sounding like a self-appointed expert.
The vids you produce aren't bad, ( this is about the 3rd of yours I've watched) but you gear your presentation as if you were speaking to 4th graders while you unbox a new toy. You seem to assume NO ONE except you has ever touched a tool before. Enthusiasm is one thing...over-selling something as routine as taking nuts off of bolts is another.
My daughter used to watch Minecraft, and the only thing I detested about it was the yelling and screaming by the (young adult) idiots who were playing and had their pics displayed in the upper corners....and who screeched and howled their way through every vid. That's what you remind me of.
Maybe people have changed back home, maybe everyone DOES have the mentality of 4th graders...(I mean, the Dems DID get a lot of votes last time from the big welfare-sustained cities) but I personally feel your actual target audience is a little older, and more mature, and would probably enjoy your vids a little more if you showed them the respect they deserve by speaking to them as adults, and toning down the hysteria just a bit.

snippet.textDisplay:
My gfs car wouldn't start one day and shops couldn't find what was wrong with it. She was about to sell it for $500 when I told her to let me have a go at it. So I pulled out the panel and got to the ignition system. Had a hunch it could be the security code thing. Cut the wire off, soldered a resistor and recoded the key, bypassing the whole deal. Now the car starts even with a screw driver, as long as you can turn the ignition 😂

But we sold it for $2500

snippet.textDisplay: this is all very familiar cause about 4 to 5 years ago I bought an suv off Ebay, a 1994 Olds Bravada, and it was from New York so it was very rusty underneath. The rust was so bad that it had eaten thru the fuel lines & when running it was spraying fuel - you could easily smell it. Obviously this was a fire hazard so I tried taking it to a mechanic but they pretty much refused to work on it (maybe an insurance liability? I dunno) So instead I went about fixing it myself. I cut out about a foot of two of the leaking fuel lines and got me some lengths of Gates rubber fuel hose and used hose clamps to secure them. This of course wasn't a proper fix but I drove the vehicle for about a year after & had no further gas leaks. Ultimately though the vehicle was just not reliable enough anymore so I ended up donating it to charity.

snippet.textDisplay:
I am really excited to see this project through. I want to follow along if I can, and I had a question that hopefully you could give me an answer to.

I am trying to get a car, and I found an 03 Chevrolet trailblazer with 319,000 miles or a 05 Chevy trailblazer with 250,000, just like the car your working on. Both of these are pretty high, and both have potential issues. The 05 has an engine knock that could be the result of a flex plate, and I don't know for sure till I check the car out for myself. The other (the 03), has little information that the owner would share online but what I could get, is that the car has some gas cap issue. Not sure if they meant to say gasket cap but its what their computer told them.

Do you think it is worth to go for either of these cars and take the risk? I found a website that quoted me 200$ to take the 05 car, if I can't fix it, and yet, I don't want to lo-ball the person offering the car. So, there is a chance I could just lose money. Its always about risk though, I understand.
(I am also dealing with potentially not having a place to work on the cars, but I am working on solutions, and already have some potential locations where I could safely work)

I have re watched so many videos of yours learning how to read and understand an engine and issues, even if I do not put it to good use. Well, I have been saving up, and a car for 500, that I could fix up and put another 500 into and resell, would go a long way towards my college tuition or a daily driver I know I could take care of.

snippet.textDisplay:
Just like selling a house - most of the market aren't DIYers. On top of this if you took the car to a garage for a quote to fit they could charge thousands. Hence why 'fixer uppers' are cheap due to the cost to repair or the perceived hassle of repair. That said you can get ahead in the game of life by developing 'trade' skills - electrical, mechanical, engineering and building. Extend that to health- an ounce of prevention is worth a pound of cure...
Thank you for sharing your knowledge and skills - you are helping people.
